WebPhonon User Manual

WebPhonon is a fully functional cross-platform multimedia player that is available for Windows and Linux.

Features:

WebPhonon uses the Phonon Multimedia framework developed by the KDE development team. By itself WebPhonon does not do any decoding or provide codecs for media files. It uses whatever video playback backend available on the Operating system that the Phonon framework supports. Currently, it uses DirectShow  on Windows, QuickTime on MacOS and Gstreamer on Linux.

WebPhonon also has capabilities for reading media urls stored in a MySQL database as well as streaming media using HTTP over a network and can therefore work as media client for an existing media server.

Installing WebPhonon:

Windows: WebPhonon is distributed as a zip archive called WebPhonon.zip available at this site:

To install this unzip the archive using Windows explorer or WinRAR to a location of your choice. To run WebPhonon just double click on the executable file WebPhonon.exe

Linux:

Ubuntu/Debian: WebPhonon is available on an Ubuntu PPA https://launchpad.net/~aaron-zakhrov/+archive/webphonon-git

Users on Ubuntu and distributions based on Ubuntu can add the PPA to their software sources and install WebPhonon from their package managers.

Debian users can download the .deb file that matches their architecture (i386 for 32 bit systems or amd64 for 64 bit systems) and launch it in their package manager.

Installing from Source: WebPhonon is available as a source archive at https://github.com/Zakhrov/WebPhonon

To build and install WebPhonon you will need the Qt and Phonon development libraries already installed on your system.

First unzip the downloaded source archive and open a command line prompt at the extracted folder.

Then run the following commands:

mkdir build

cd build

qmake ..

make

Then run the following command as root or sudo:

make install

After installation WebPhonon should show up in your applications menu like so:

 
 

WebPhonon UI Overview:

This is the main WebPhonon window:

 

It has a main toolbar that holds all the media playback, file handling and database management controls. It also has a seek slider and a volume slider. Apart from those controls it has a table for viewing files currently queued and a text field for entering a url for a media stream.

 
Playing local media files:
 

To play a media file stored locally on the hard drive, either click the

icon or go to File->Open->local file in the File menu. A new dialog box will pop up where you can select the media file. WebPhonon will only let you open one file at a time.

This is the open file dialog:

Once the file is selected, you can either press the “Enter” key or click on Open and the file will play automatically. Depending on the video resolution, WebPhonon will scale the video to the maximum size it can within the confines of the main window.
 
 
You can scale the video higher by hiding the url bar and the playlist table by clicking on the icon or going to Database->Hide table.
 

 

Playing URLs and media streams:

WebPhonon can also play media streams over the HTTP protocol. Right now, this does not include Youtube URLs or links from other Youtube-like sites. This is because, by default Youtube links are dynamic PHP pages that include their own flash player which cannot be read by WebPhonon.

To play a stream click on the icon or go to File->Open->Http Stream.

The Url bar will the appear, type or paste the url into the url bar and then click on the launch button. Once the launch button is clicked, the url bar is automatically hidden.

Playing from a database:

WebPhonon can read media file paths stored in a MySQL database. To load data from a database click the icon. This will pop up the following dialog:
Here you have to enter the database hostname (if your database is on the same computer as WebPhonon this will be localhost), your database name the user name and password and the table name. These details can be given to you by your database/network administrator.
 

Once all the information has been entered, click on OK to load the database or Cancel to drop the changes.

Once the database has been loaded, click on the   icon or go to File->Open->From Database to play the media from the database.
